===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*med-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|medicin}}, borrowed from {{bor|en|frm|medicine}}, from {{der|en|fro|medecine}}, from {{der|en|la|medicīna|t=the healing art, medicine, a physician's shop, a remedy, medicine}}, feminine of {{m|la|medicīnus|t=of or belonging to physic or surgery, or to a physician or surgeon}}, from {{m|la|medicus|t=a physician, surgeon}}.

The extended sense of "Indigenous magic" is a {{calque|en|oj|mashkiki|t=medicine|nocap=1}}  or {{m|oj|mide}} (or cognates in {{w|Algonquian languages|related languages}}) when used in compounds such as [[Grand Medicine Society]], [[medicine lodge]], [[medicine dance]], [[medicine bag]], [[medicine wheel]], [[medicine man]], [[Medicine Line]], and [[bad medicine]] or place names such as [[Medicine Hat]], [[Medicine Creek]], etc.

